  "prompt": "Why is New York Mets pitcher Matt Harvey called \"The Dark Knight\"? Did the team and MLB get permission from DC Comics for his Batman-themed merchandise?",
  "response": "Matt Harvey, the former New York Mets pitcher, earned the nickname \"The Dark Knight\" due to his dominant pitching performances and his perceived dark, brooding persona, which was likened to the Batman character. The nickname gained popularity after a 2013 article by *Sports Illustrated* compared Harvey's demeanor and success on the mound to the superhero.\n\nRegarding the use of Batman-themed merchandise, neither Matt Harvey nor the New York Mets need explicit permission from DC Comics to use the nickname \"The Dark Knight,\" as it is a public domain phrase and not directly tied to DC Comics' intellectual property. However, if official merchandise directly incorporates Batman imagery, logos, or other copyrighted elements from DC Comics, then permission and licensing agreements would be required. In such cases, MLB or the team would typically negotiate with DC Comics to ensure compliance with intellectual property laws.\n\nIn Harvey's case, his nickname and related merchandise likely avoided copyright issues by focusing on the phrase \"The Dark Knight\" without directly using Batman-specific designs, which allowed them to operate without needing DC Comics' approval.",
